.TH shell_default 3 "stdlib 7.3" "Ericsson AB" "Erlang Module Definition"
.SH NAME
shell_default \- Customizing the Erlang environment.

.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
The functions in this module are called when no module name is specified in a shell command.

.PP
Consider the following shell dialog:

.IP
.nf
1> lists:reverse("abc").
"cba"
2> c(foo).
{ok, foo}

.fi

.PP
In command one, module \fIlists\fR is called. In command two, no module name is specified. The shell searches module \fIuser_default\fR followed by module \fIshell_default\fR for function \fIc/1\fR.

.PP
\fIshell_default\fR is intended for "system wide" customizations to the shell. \fIuser_default\fR is intended for "local" or individual user customizations.

.SS "Hint"

.PP
To add your own commands to the shell, create a module called \fIuser_default\fR and add the commands you want. Then add the following line as the \fIfirst\fR line in your \fI.erlang\fR file in your home directory.

.IP
.nf
code:load_abs("$PATH/user_default").

.fi

.PP
\fI$PATH\fR is the directory where your \fIuser_default\fR module can be found.

.SH FUNCTIONS
.LP
.B
\fBhelp() -> true.\fR

.br
.RS
.PP
Print the help for all shell commands.


.RE
